dst 0.1 - dynamic suckless terminal
-----------------------------------
dst 0.1 is a fork of st 0.9.3 you configure with a runtime text file and patch
declaratively - no recompiling to change settings.

It keeps st's minimalism (small diff against upstream, no extra
dependencies) but moves everyday settings out of config.h and into a
plain-text file read at startup, in the style of an rc file. A separate
`dst --rebuild` step manages which upstream st patches are compiled in,
driven by the same config file.


What's different from st
------------------------
1. Runtime configuration. dst reads ~/.config/dst/config (or
   $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/dst/config) at startup and applies it over the
   compiled-in defaults. Edit the file, relaunch - no recompile. See
   config.sample for every directive. Precedence is:
       compiled defaults  <  config file  <  command-line flags

2. Declarative patches. Lines like
       include https://st.suckless.org/patches/scrollback/st-scrollback-0.9.2.diff
   are ignored on a normal launch and read only by `dst --rebuild`, which
   fetches each diff, applies it to a clean source tree, rebuilds, and
   installs the result only on success (a failed build never replaces the
   working binary).

Keybindings and shortcuts remain compile-time (config.def.h) for now.


Requirements
------------
In order to build dst you need the Xlib header files.
`dst --rebuild` additionally uses cc, make, patch and curl at runtime.


Installation
------------
Edit config.mk to match your local setup (dst is installed into the
/usr/local namespace by default).

Afterwards enter the following command to build and install dst (if
necessary as root):

    make clean install


Running dst
-----------
If you did not install dst with make clean install, you must compile the
terminfo entry with the following command:

    tic -sx st.info

dst keeps st's terminfo (TERM=st-256color) for application compatibility.
See the man page (man dst) for configuration and rebuild details.


Configuration
-------------
Copy the sample and edit it:

    mkdir -p ~/.config/dst
    cp config.sample ~/.config/dst/config

Then relaunch dst. To change which patches are built in, add or remove
`include` lines and run `dst --rebuild`.


Credits
-------
Based on st (https://st.suckless.org) by the suckless community, which
